Telescoping Series
The technique demonstrated in this section is called telescopic cancelling.
Like a telescope, the middle section collapses (by cancelling) leaving just the outer terms to be computed.

Example 2.1 Find the constants a and b such that \dfrac{1}{k(k+1)}=\dfrac{a}{k} + \dfrac{b}{k+1}, for all k\in \mathbb{N}.
Hence, prove that \dfrac{1}{1\times2}+\dfrac{1}{2\times3}+\dfrac{1}{3\times 4}+\dots +\dfrac{1}{n(n+1)}=\dfrac{n}{n+1}



